{"ts": "2026-06-09T00:12:54.548706+00:00", "update": {"model": {"messages": [{"type": "ai", "data": {"content": "Here's a walkthrough of the three database migrations in this repository, in the order they'd be applied:\n\n---\n\n### Migration 1: `001_create_users.sql` — Create the `users` table\n\n```sql\nCREATE TABLE users (\n    id           BIGSERIAL PRIMARY KEY,\n    email        TEXT UNIQUE NOT NULL,\n    display_name TEXT,\n    created_at   TIMESTAMPTZ NOT NULL DEFAULT now()\n);\n```\n\n**What it does:** Creates the foundational `users` table with four columns:\n\n- **`id`** — An auto-incrementing 64-bit integer serving as the primary key (`BIGSERIAL`).\n- **`email`** — A required text field with a `UNIQUE` constraint (no two users can share an email).\n- **`display_name`** — An optional text field for a human-readable name.\n- **`created_at`** — A timestamp with time zone that defaults to the current time when the row is inserted.\n\nThis is the base table that everything else builds on.\n\n---\n\n### Migration 2: `002_create_sessions.sql` — Create the `sessions` table\n\n```sql\nCREATE TABLE sessions (\n    id          UUID PRIMARY KEY,\n    user_id     BIGINT NOT NULL REFERENCES users(id) ON DELETE CASCADE,\n    issued_at   TIMESTAMPTZ NOT NULL DEFAULT now(),\n    expires_at  TIMESTAMPTZ NOT NULL\n);\n```\n\n**What it does:** Creates a `sessions` table to track user login sessions:\n\n- **`id`** — A UUID serving as the primary key (good for session tokens).\n- **`user_id`** — A foreign key referencing `users(id)`. The `ON DELETE CASCADE` clause means if a user is deleted, all their sessions are automatically cleaned up.\n- **`issued_at`** — When the session was created (defaults to now).\n- **`expires_at`** — When the session expires. There is **no** index on this column yet, which is notable (see migration 3).\n\nThis migration depends on migration 1 because of the foreign key to `users`.\n\n---\n\n### Migration 3: `003_add_session_index.sql` — Add an index on `sessions.user_id`\n\n```sql\nCREATE INDEX idx_sessions_user_id ON sessions(user_id);\n```\n\n**What it does:** Adds a B-tree index on the `user_id` column of the `sessions` table. This optimizes queries that look up all sessions belonging to a particular user (e.g., \"list this user's active sessions\" or \"revoke all sessions for this user\"). Without this index, PostgreSQL would need to do a full table scan on `sessions` for any `WHERE user_id = ?` query.\n\n---\n\n### How they're applied\n\nThe repo includes a runner script at `scripts/apply_migrations.sh` that applies these files in lexicographic order (which is why the numeric prefixes `001`, `002`, `003` matter). There's also a `scripts/reset.sh` that presumably drops everything and re-applies from scratch.\n\n### Quick summary table\n\n| # | File | Action | Depends on |\n|---|------|--------|------------|\n| 1 | `001_create_users.sql` | Create `users` table | — |\n| 2 | `002_create_sessions.sql` | Create `sessions` table (FK → `users`) | 1 |\n| 3 | `003_add_session_index.sql` | Index `sessions(user_id)` | 2 |\n\nOverall it's a clean, minimal schema: users authenticate and get sessions, with cascade deletes and an index for fast user→session lookups. Let me know if you want to dig into the seed data or any other part of the repo!", "additional_kwargs": {"refusal": null}, "response_metadata": {"token_usage": {"completion_tokens": 805, "prompt_tokens": 7969, "total_tokens": 8774, "completion_tokens_details": {"accepted_prediction_tokens": null, "audio_tokens": 0, "reasoning_tokens": 14, "rejected_prediction_tokens": null, "image_tokens": 0}, "prompt_tokens_details": {"audio_tokens": 0, "cached_tokens": 6208, "cache_write_tokens": 0, "video_tokens": 0}, "cost": 0, "is_byok": true, "cost_details": {"upstream_inference_cost": 0.0014887338, "upstream_inference_prompt_cost": 0.0007883838, "upstream_inference_completions_cost": 0.00070035}}, "model_provider": "openai", "model_name": "xiaomi/mimo-v2.5-pro-2026042